1 Integrate-and-Fire Neuron with A Refractory Period (4 points)¶

Please modify the leaky integrate-and-fire model to produce the following dynamics showing refractory/inactivation periods like the following:

Unlike the above figure, you need to produce "spikes" in your implementation.

1.0 The Leaky Integrate-and-Fire Model¶

In [143]:
def IFmodel(I, g, C, Vrst, Vthr, Vspk):
    dt=.1; V=[Vrst];
    for t in np.arange(0,10,dt):
        V1=V[-1] # the last element
        s=V1>Vthr; # An implicit IF-THEN hack
        V2=s*Vrst+(1-s)*(V1+dt/C*(-g*V1+I)) # Euler integration
        V1=s*Vspk+(1-s)*V1 # Spiking now?
        V[-1]=V1; V.append(V2)

    plot(V);

# Please write your codes here.
I=2;g=5;C=10;Vrst=0;Vthr=.3;Vspk=1;rfperiod=10

dt=.1; V=[Vrst];
for t in np.arange(0,10,dt):
    V1=V[-1] # the last element
    if V1==0 and t!=0:
        V.extend([0]*rfperiod)  
    s=V1>Vthr; # An implicit IF-THEN hack
    V2=s*Vrst+(1-s)*(V1+dt/C*(-g*V1+I)) # Euler integration
    V1=s*Vspk+(1-s)*V1 # Spiking now?
    V[-1]=V1; V.append(V2)

plot(V);

2 The Hodgkin–Huxley Model (4 points)¶

Please read P.19, P.20, & P.21 of the article by Hodgkin & Huxley (1952) to implement the very original HodgkinHuxley model using their equations and parameters. You should observe something like Fig.22 in their paper.

2.0 Modern implementation of the H-H model¶

In [36]:
# Integration of Hodgkin--Huxley equations with Euler method
g=np.array([36, 120, 0.3]) # Maximal conductances (in units of mS/cm^2); 
# 1=K, 2=Na, 3=l
E=np.array([-12, 115, 10.613]) # Resting potentials (in mV):
# Some initializations: some variables
gnmh=np.zeros(3); Alpha=np.zeros(3); Beta=np.zeros(3); x=np.zeros(3); 
x[2]=1; I_ext=0; V=[-10]; dt=0.01; 

tspan=np.arange(0,50,dt)
for t in tspan:
    
    V1=V[-1] # the last element
    if(t>=10 and t<=40):
        I_ext=10  # turns external current on when t=[10,40]
    else:  
        I_ext=0   
        
  # alpha functions:
    Alpha[0]=0.01*(10-V1)/(np.exp((10-V1)/10)-1)
    Alpha[1]=0.1*(25-V1)/(np.exp((25-V1)/10)-1)
    Alpha[2]=0.07*np.exp(-V1/20)
    
  # beta functions:
    Beta[0]=0.125*np.exp(-V1/80)
    Beta[1]=4*np.exp(-V1/18)
    Beta[2]=1/(np.exp((30-V1)/10)+1)
    
  # tau_x and x_0 (x=0,1,2) are defined with alpha and beta
    tau=1/(Alpha+Beta);
    x_inf=Alpha*tau;
    x=x+dt*(x_inf-x)/tau;
    
  # calculate actual conductances g with given n, m, h
    gnmh[0]=g[0]*x[0]**4;
    gnmh[1]=g[1]*x[1]**3*x[2];
    gnmh[2]=g[2];
    
  # Ohm's law
    I=gnmh*(V1-E);
    V2=V1+dt*(I_ext-sum(I))
    V.append(V2)
    
plot(tspan,V[:-1]); 
xlabel('Time'); ylabel('Voltage');

2.1 Your implementation of the original H-H model¶

In [172]:
# Please write your codes here.
def HHmodel(ext_current):
    g=np.array([36, 120, 0.3]) # Maximal conductances (in units of mS/cm^2); 
    # 1=K, 2=Na, 3=l
    E=np.array([12, -115, -10.613]) 
    # Resting potentials [VK, VNa, Vl] (in mV):
    # Some initializations: some variables
    gnmh=np.zeros(3); Alpha=np.zeros(3); Beta=np.zeros(3); x=np.zeros(3); 
    x[2]=1; # I_ext=0; 
    V=[30]; dt=0.01; 

    tspan=np.arange(0,50,dt)
    for t in tspan:

        V1=V[-1] # the last element
        if(t>=10 and t<=40):
            I_ext=ext_current  # turns external current on when t=[10,40]
        else:  
            I_ext=0   

      # alpha functions:
        Alpha[0]=0.01*(10+V1)/(np.exp((10+V1)/10)-1)
        Alpha[1]=0.1*(25+V1)/(np.exp((25+V1)/10)-1)
        Alpha[2]=0.07*np.exp(V1/20)

      # beta functions:
        Beta[0]=0.125*np.exp(V1/80)
        Beta[1]=4*np.exp(V1/18)
        Beta[2]=1/(np.exp((30+V1)/10)+1)

      # tau_x and x_0 (x=0,1,2) are defined with alpha and beta
        tau=1/(Alpha+Beta);
        x_inf=Alpha*tau;
        x=x+dt*(x_inf-x)/tau;

      # calculate actual conductances g with given n, m, h
        gnmh[0]=g[0]*x[0]**4;
        gnmh[1]=g[1]*x[1]**3*x[2];
        gnmh[2]=g[2];

      # Ohm's law
        I=gnmh*(V1-E);
        V2=V1+dt*(I_ext-sum(I))
        V.append(V2)

    negV = [i*(-1) for i in V]
    fig, ax = subplots()
    ax.plot(tspan,negV[:-1])
    ax.spines['right'].set_color('none') # hide
#     ax.yaxis.tick_left()
    ax.spines['bottom'].set_position('zero')
    ax.spines['top'].set_color('none')
#     ax.xaxis.tick_bottom()
    xlabel('Time (msec)')
    ylabel('Voltage (mV)')
    show()
